// How Local Variables Work in Stack Memory

When a Java program runs:

    1 > main() method starts first â†’ JVM creates a stack frame for it.
    2 > When main() calls another method (m1()), a new stack frame is created on top of main()'s frame.
    3 > If m1() calls m2(), then again a new stack frame is created for m2().
    4 > Each methods local variables are stored inside its own stack frame.
    5 > When the method ends, its stack frame is deleted, so its local variables are also destroyed.

class StackMemoryExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Main started");
        m1();
        System.out.println("Main ended");
    }

    public static void m1() {
        int a = 10; // local variable in m1()
        System.out.println("In m1(), a = " + a);
        m2();
    }

    public static void m2() {
        int b = 20; // local variable in m2()
        System.out.println("In m2(), b = " + b);
    }
}


  Stack Memory Representation
------------------------------
|  m2() Stack Frame          |
|  int b = 20                |
------------------------------
|  m1() Stack Frame          |
|  int a = 10                |
------------------------------
|  main() Stack Frame        |
|  args[], etc.              |
------------------------------
        Stack Memory

Execution Flow

    main() starts â†’ stack frame for main.
    m1() is called â†’ new stack frame created for m1, local var a lives there.
    m2() is called â†’ new stack frame created for m2, local var b lives there.
    When m2() finishes â†’ its stack frame is deleted, variable b is gone.
    Then m1() finishes â†’ its stack frame is deleted, variable a is gone.
    Finally, main() finishes â†’ program ends, its stack frame is deleted.

Key Rule

ðŸ‘‰ Local variables cannot be used outside their method because they live only inside their stack frame.








